x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b><i>Tara Palmeri<=
/i>: You=E2=80=99ve been driving the Democrats in Washington, D.C., absolut=
ely apoplectic with your tweets predicting Trump wins Nevada. Last week, yo=
u told me you were seeing the most unusual turnout patterns you=E2=80=99ve =
seen since you started tracking elections in 1986. Is that still the case t=
oday?</b><br/><br/><i>Jon Ralston</i>: It=E2=80=99s certainly the most unus=
ual turnout pattern since these things have been available to track. Nevada=
 used to be a pretty reliably red state, but it=E2=80=99s been blue for the=
 last four cycles. Yet in all of those cycles, the Republicans never had a =
lead <i>ever</i> during early voting, and now they=E2=80=99ve built up a pr=
etty substantial lead. At the time we=E2=80=99re talking, they have more th=
an a 32,000-vote lead statewide in ballots. <br/><br/>There=E2=80=99s defin=
itely concern among Democrats, both here and nationally.
They still think it=E2=80=99s going to be a close race in Nevada, and that =
they=E2=80=99re going to win independents, who are 40 percent of registered=
 voters. But remember, Democrats are saying the <i>best-</i>case scenario i=
s that they win this by 10,000 votes or so out of 1.4 million cast. So even=
 if it=E2=80=99s close, that=E2=80=99s going to take a lot for them to do t=
hat.<br/><br/><b>What have Democrats been doing to get their voters out? Ha=
ve you seen any uptick in activity?</b><br/><br/>They=E2=80=99re pulling ou=
t all the stops: bringing in celebrities, doing all kinds of events. But th=
e turnout here has also changed. During Covid, we became primarily a mail b=
allot state. So suddenly, mail ballots are really important. Democrats love=
 voting by mail. And so they still think that the mail ballots are going to=
 change the turnout pattern in their favor. In 2020, Republicans=E2=80=99 m=
essaging was. <i>Mail balloting is evil</i>;<i> early voting was not great<=
/i>;<i> just vote on Election Day</i>. Well, now
the Trump campaign is sending out texts telling his voters to vote early, v=
ote by mail, and all the rest of it. So they=E2=80=99re cannibalizing part =
of the Election Day vote. <br/><br/><b>Where are we at right now in terms o=
f returns?</b><br/><br/>For the last two cycles, 80 and 90 percent of the v=
ote has been in before Election Day, and right now, we=E2=80=99re probably =
at about half the vote being in. It depends on how many people vote. I thin=
k it=E2=80=99s about just under 650,000, and the turnout is probably going =
to be about 1.3 million to 1.4 million. So you got half the vote in already=
, which is why the Republicans are so optimistic. Historically, the Republi=
cans usually do well in the first few days of early voting in the second we=
ek. We just started the second week, so if they do well Monday and Tuesday,=
 I think the concern turns to panic for the Democrats.<br/><br/><b>Why do y=
ou think Republicans are coming out so enthusiastically for Trump right now=
?</b><br/><br/>=E2=80=9CNo taxes on
tips=E2=80=9D was a very smart thing the Trump campaign did to try to peel =
away the culinary workers from their union leadership, and we=E2=80=99ll se=
e how that works. But the real reason for this is because of the rural vote=
=2E Nevada has 17 counties; two of=
 them are urban=E2=80=94Reno and Vegas=E2=
=80=94and then the rest are very deep red, and they have turned out disprop=
ortionately so far in the early going. That=E2=80=99s the reason the Republ=
icans have a lead=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s almost all because there=E2=80=99s t=
his huge surplus of rural ballots so far. As I said, if in a few days that =
doesn=E2=80=99t start to change for the Democrats, they=E2=80=99re going to=
 get worried that there=E2=80=99s going to be carnage up and down the ballo=
t, including the Senate race, potentially.<br/><br/><b>Are these rural vote=
rs the first-time and low-propensity voters that Trump=E2=80=99s team is re=
ally banking on?</b><br/><br/>No, they=E2=80=99re the opposite of that, in =
general. The rural counties have gone by landslide margins for Republicans,=
 and especially for
Trump in 2016 and 2020, and so I think it could be an even bigger landslide=
=2E Usually, the margin in rural cou=
nties can=E2=80=99t offset the huge amoun=
t of Democratic votes in Clark County because there are so many more votes.=
 But that may not be the case this time; Democrats are worried about it, an=
d Republicans sound supremely confident here. <br/></td>
